{
    "esm": "0.4.0",
    "metadata": {
        "name": "McTigueModel",
        "description": "McTigue (1987) finite-sphere model for volcanic surface deformation. Extends the Mogi (1958) point-source model by incorporating higher-order correction terms that account for the finite radius of a spherical deformation source. The correction depends on ε = a/d and improves accuracy for larger ε: within 5% of FE models for ε < 0.59, vs ε < 0.37 for Mogi. Three purely-algebraic equations: R = sqrt(x²+d²) (source-to-surface distance), Ur = (Mogi_Ur) × C (Eq. 3, radial displacement), Uz = (Mogi_Uz) × C (Eq. 4, vertical displacement), where C = 1 + (a/d)³ × [(1+ν)/(2(−7+5ν)) + 15d²(−2+ν)/(4R²(−7+5ν))] is the McTigue finite-sphere correction factor. Migrated from Geodynamics.jl@d680af419676cc576d60b16af0d3dd40c0b23eea src/mogi_mctigue.jl:107 (`McTigueModel` @component).",
        "tags": [
            "geodynamics",
            "volcanic-deformation",
            "mctigue",
            "mogi",
            "observed-only",
            "algebraic"
        ],
        "created": "2026-05-21T00:00:00Z",
        "authors": [
            "Geodynamics.jl contributors",
            "EarthSciModels migration (esm-it82)"
        ],
        "references": [
            {
                "citation": "McTigue, D.F., 1987. Elastic stress and deformation near a finite spherical magma body: resolution of the point source paradox. J. Geophys. Res. 92 (B12), 12931–12940. https://doi.org/10.1029/JB092iB12p12931. Equations 3–4 implemented here."
            },
            {
                "citation": "Taylor, N.C., Johnson, J.H., Herd, R.A. (2021). Making the most of the Mogi model: Size matters. Journal of Volcanology and Geothermal Research, 419, 107380. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jvolgeores.2021.107380. Table 1 test parameters and Equations 3–4 form used here."
            },
            {
                "citation": "Mogi, K., 1958. Relations between the eruptions of various volcanoes and the deformations of the ground surfaces around them. Bull. Earthq. Res. Inst. 36, 99–134."
            }
        ]
    },
    "models": {
        "McTigueModel": {
            "reference": {
                "notes": "source_ref: Geodynamics.jl@d680af419676cc576d60b16af0d3dd40c0b23eea:src/mogi_mctigue.jl:107\n\nUpstream `McTigueModel` is an MTK `@component` implementing the McTigue (1987) finite-sphere analytical model for volcanic ground deformation. It declares 6 `@parameters` (G, ν, ΔP, a, d, x) and 3 time-indexed `@variables` (R, Ur, Uz), with 3 equations returning `System(eqs, t; name)`. The upstream Julia test confirms `length(unknowns(mtkcompile(sys))) == 0` — after structural simplification, all 3 variables are algebraic observed quantities (zero dynamic states).\n\nSystem kind: all 3 upstream equations are explicit algebraic assignments with no `D(.)` operator. The dependency chain is strictly forward (R computed first, then Ur and Uz both depend on R), so the system is triangular — no implicit Newton solve is required, and `system_kind` is left unset (default, zero differential states), exactly as for MogiModel and the sibling observed-only components AnelasticMassContinuity, AtmosphericDiffusion, etc.\n\nNote on migration tracker blocking gap. The tracker lists this bead as `gt-ebuq (init_eq/system_kind=nonlinear)`. Investigation of the upstream source confirms the equations are EXPLICITLY algebraic — no `initialization_equations`, no `guesses`, and no implicit coupling. The `system_kind=nonlinear` label was applied conservatively to the whole Geodynamics group. The Julia test constructs a `NonlinearProblem` only because MTK compiles all-algebraic `System`s to that type internally — not because the equations require iteration. The migration therefore uses the explicit-algebraic path without `system_kind`, matching MogiModel (components/geodynamics/mogi.esm) exactly.\n\nNote on `one_m` constant. The upstream declares `one_m = 1.0 [unit = u\"m\"]` and writes `R ~ (x^2/one_m^2 + d^2/one_m^2)^0.5 * one_m` to satisfy DynamicQuantities' requirement that sqrt arguments be dimensionless. Since ESM has no dimensional quantity tracking in expression trees, `one_m` is mathematically 1.0 and the equation reduces to `R = sqrt(x^2 + d^2)` with no loss of precision.\n\nMcTigue correction factor. The finite-sphere correction C in Eqs. 3–4 is:\n  C = 1 + ε³ × [(1+ν)/(2(−7+5ν)) + 15d²(−2+ν)/(4R²(−7+5ν))]\nwhere ε = a/d. The correction is identical for Ur and Uz — both displacements are scaled by the same factor C relative to the Mogi result. At ν=0.25 and ε=0.25 (Table 1 params: a=1 km, d=4 km), C ≈ 1.005261 (0.5% correction). At ε=0.4 (a=800 m, d=2 km, Kīlauea), C ≈ 1.01552 (1.6% correction). When ε→0, C→1 and McTigue reduces exactly to Mogi.\n\nParameters (6): G (shear modulus, Pa), ν (Poisson's ratio, dimensionless), ΔP (source overpressure, Pa), a (source radius, m), d (source depth, m), x (horizontal distance from source, m).\n\nState variables (3): R (source-to-surface distance, m), Ur (horizontal-radial surface displacement, m), Uz (vertical surface displacement, m).\n\nEquation faithfulness. The 3 equations from src/mogi_mctigue.jl:155-178 are preserved in order:\n  1. R ~ sqrt(x^2 + d^2)\n  2. Ur ~ (a^3 * ΔP * (1-ν) * x / (G * R^3)) * (1 + (a/d)^3 * ((1+ν)/(2(−7+5ν)) + 15d²(−2+ν)/(4R²(−7+5ν))))  (Eq. 3, Taylor et al.)\n  3. Uz ~ (a^3 * ΔP * (1-ν) * d / (G * R^3)) * (1 + (a/d)^3 * ((1+ν)/(2(−7+5ν)) + 15d²(−2+ν)/(4R²(−7+5ν))))  (Eq. 4, Taylor et al.)\n\nDefault values match Table 1 of Taylor et al. (2021): G=4 GPa, ν=0.25, ΔP=2 MPa, a=1 km, d=4 km, x=5 km.\n\nTolerance rationale. Closed-form algebraic evaluation — no ODE integration, no implicit solve — so there is no integrator error to bound; rel=1e-6 covers float64 round-off in the power/multiply/divide chains."
            },
            "tolerance": {
                "rel": 1.0e-6
            },
            "variables": {
                "G": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "Pa",
                    "default": 4.0e9,
                    "description": "Shear modulus (Pa) of the elastic half-space. Controls the stiffness of the medium — a higher G yields smaller displacements for the same overpressure. Upstream MTK `@parameter`; default 4.0 GPa, the value used in Taylor et al. (2021) Table 1 for Kīlauea volcano rock."
                },
                "ν": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "1",
                    "default": 0.25,
                    "description": "Poisson's ratio (dimensionless) of the elastic half-space. Typical values for crustal rock are 0.25–0.30. Appears as (1−ν) in the displacement formulas and (1+ν) / (−7+5ν) in the McTigue correction term. Upstream MTK `@parameter`; default 0.25."
                },
                "ΔP": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "Pa",
                    "default": 2.0e6,
                    "description": "Source overpressure (Pa) — the excess pressure inside the spherical magma chamber above the far-field lithostatic stress. Positive ΔP (inflation) produces positive outward radial displacement (Ur > 0) and positive vertical uplift (Uz > 0); negative ΔP (deflation) reverses both. Both Ur and Uz scale linearly with ΔP. Upstream MTK `@parameter`; default 2.0 MPa (Table 1 of Taylor et al. 2021)."
                },
                "a": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m",
                    "default": 1000.0,
                    "description": "Source radius (m) — the radius of the spherical magma chamber. Appears in both the Mogi a³ pre-factor and the McTigue correction through ε = a/d. The McTigue model is valid when ε = a/d < 0.59 (Taylor et al. 2021, ~5% FE error); for larger ε, finite-source non-linearity dominates and this analytical approximation degrades. Upstream MTK `@parameter`; default 1000 m (1 km, Table 1 of Taylor et al. 2021)."
                },
                "d": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m",
                    "default": 4000.0,
                    "description": "Source depth (m) — the depth of the center of the spherical magma chamber below the free surface. Enters the source-to-surface distance R, the Mogi denominator, the McTigue correction term numerator (15d²) and denominator (4R²). Upstream MTK `@parameter`; default 4000 m (4 km, Table 1 of Taylor et al. 2021)."
                },
                "x": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m",
                    "default": 5000.0,
                    "description": "Horizontal distance from source (m) — the radial distance on the free surface from the point directly above the source center. Enters R and Ur. Upstream MTK `@parameter`; default 5000 m (5 km, Table 1 evaluation point)."
                },
                "R": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "m",
                    "description": "Distance from source center to surface evaluation point (m): R = sqrt(x^2 + d^2). Auxiliary variable computed first in the explicit triangular system; used in both the Mogi pre-factor (R^3) and the McTigue correction (R^2). Upstream MTK `@variable` with time index; no time derivative present, no initial condition (observed/algebraic)."
                },
                "Ur": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "m",
                    "description": "Horizontal-radial surface displacement (m) due to source overpressure (Eq. 3, Taylor et al. 2021): Ur = a^3 * ΔP * (1−ν) * x / (G * R^3) * C, where C is the McTigue finite-sphere correction. Positive for inflation (ΔP > 0) and outward from the source (x > 0). Larger than the Mogi estimate for ε > 0 (for ν=0.25, correction C > 1). Upstream MTK `@variable`; observed/algebraic, no time derivative."
                },
                "Uz": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "m",
                    "description": "Vertical surface displacement (m) due to source overpressure (Eq. 4, Taylor et al. 2021): Uz = a^3 * ΔP * (1−ν) * d / (G * R^3) * C, where C is the same McTigue finite-sphere correction as Ur. Positive for inflation (ΔP > 0, uplift). Larger than the Mogi estimate for ε > 0 (for ν=0.25). The Ur/Uz ratio for McTigue is x/d × C_x/C_d — not exactly x/d as in Mogi — because C depends on R and R depends on x. Upstream MTK `@variable`; observed/algebraic, no time derivative."
                }
            },
